<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34035a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34035a">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34035a"> 35(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> violating cyclic / order <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34035a"><li>FW 285.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#n34035a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/l39lg.htm#n34035a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34035a">MS BL 47478-45</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:123 <a name="lgd8" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lgd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd8.htm#n34035a">Draft: II.2&sect;8.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">If the letters <i>a</i>, <i>b</i> and <i>c</i> are written in that order on the perimeter of a circle, then we are observing cyclic order when we write <font color="green">[in an algebraic expression]</font> <i>b</i>-<i>c</i>, <i>c</i>-<i>a</i>, <i>a</i>-<i>b</i>, moving round clockwise; or <i>c</i>-<i>b</i>, <i>b</i>-<i>a</i>, <i>a</i>-<i>c</i>, moving in the opposite direction. We are <mark>violating cyclic order</mark> by the use of arrangements such as <i>b</i>-<i>c</i>, <i>a</i>-<i>c</i>, <i>a</i>-<i>b</i>, or <i>a</i>-<i>c</i>, <i>b</i>-<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>-<i>c</i>. <small> Hall &amp; Knight, <a name="HSHK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HSHK"><cite title="source">Elementary Algebra for Schools</cite></a> (n.d) 158</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
